    {
      "test": "ruby_io_popen_with_user_input_via_compute_taint",
      "file": "crates/tldr-core/tests/rr_module_function_integ_test.rs",
      "line": 193,
      "sibling_milestone": "ruby-bare-call-extraction-v1 (TBD follow-on)",
      "added_in": "M4-amendment-2026-04-29",
      "reason": "Documented FAI-v1 M5 carry-forward (commit 7849b3f). Tree-sitter-ruby parses bare `gets` as identifier (not call), so AST `call_names: ['gets']` cannot cover it. FAI-v1 M5 retained the regex `\\bgets\\b` in RUBY_PATTERNS.sources as 'Option A'. Under analyze_ast_only (the test harness FAI-v1 M1 added), the regex bank is short-circuited — so this test fails BY DESIGN. Has been failing since FAI-v1 M5 shipped; M1 enumeration mis-cataloged as Cat-C orthogonal-real because the M1 worker did not cross-reference FAI-v1 M5 carry-forward documentation. Follow-on milestone (ruby-bare-call-extraction-v1) can close the AST-only gap by either (a) emitting a synthetic 'call' for bare-identifier method invocations in Ruby's AST adapter, or (b) extending the AST-only source bank with a Ruby-specific bareword bank parallel to call_names."
